collation.p:
The manuscript comprises sixteen quires of eight leaves, plus a final, imperfect quire.
Quires 1-168 (ff. 1-128)
Quire 178-4 (ff. 129-132: 5th-8th leaves, after f. 132, missing)

seg.seg: Text: Ruled with leadpoint, 28 lines. Written above top line in long lines, on alternate lines and in larger script than the gloss, almost always occupying the full length of the text block (occasionally lines of gloss extend underneath the final line of text), but varying in width, even on the same page. Pricking marks for the outer bounding lines only.

Gloss: Ruled with leadpoint for 39-55 lines of gloss, not all occupied, written in smaller script. Written above top line in 1, 2 or sometimes 3 columns, of varying width, even on the same page, and which sometimes overlap with one another.

layout.seg: Paratext: Chapter numbers added a little later, in the margins.

handNote.p: Written by a single scribe in English protogothic bookhand.

decoNote.p: The text of each book opens with a large arabesque initial in blue, green or red and a title in red and green capitals. The capitula open with a large blue initial with arabesque ornament in green, red and blue. Jerome's prologue opens with a red, blue and green arabesque initial.
Small initials, plain or arabesqued in red, green and yellow (or combinations thereof).
Sections of text and gloss are divided by red, green or occasionally blue initials, plain or ornamented in the other colour. There are also many small red or green initials.

binding.p: Original, repaired by Douglas Cockerell Cockerell, Douglas and Son in 1971, the spine replaced under the old skin and two paper endleaves supplied at the front and the rear. Tawed skin over flush, square-edged oak boards; resewn on four bands slightly raised on the flat spine. Tabs with the remains of blue perimeter sewing. Modern blue and white endbands. Mark of a chain-staple at the head of the front cover, two at the foot. Originally an overcover. Formerly two narrow straps of thick tawed skin from recesses in the front board, from under the cover skin to pins at the rear; replaced by a wider central strap and pin fastening.

provenance.p: Perhaps recorded in a 12th-century book-list of the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds (CBMLC 4, B13.223).
Ex libris, title and pressmark (B.58), written by the hand of Henry Kirkestede (c. 1314-c. 1379) Kirkestede, Henry, approximately 1314-approximately 1378 (f. 1r).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Rodney M. Thomson, A descriptive catalogue of the medieval manuscripts at Pembroke College, Cambridge (2022) (used here by kind permission of the author).

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
